////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
// Acid Test: Unsupported Declarations
//
// A declaration body may not contain another declaration - the scope of such
// an inner declaration is not legible to a user, since it depends on the
// placement of the invisible body copy.  Quantified properties in a body
// should use the formal quantifiers instead.
//
// This input used to crash validation when the body was a bare declaration
// (the inner declaration's body copy was inserted inside the outer
// Declaration node, corrupting its structure).  Now such declarations are
// flagged 'unsupported' during interpretation:
//
//   - no copy of their body is inserted, so their content is inert (they
//     keep only their atomic propositional form);
//   - they receive an 'inapplicable' validation result with reason
//     'unsupported declaration' (the ⊘ marker in Lode and the web UI) and a
//     scoping error { unsupported: [...] } (the web UI hover message);
//   - the rest of the document validates normally around them.
//
// Each section below uses its own disjoint constants so that rules and
// instantiations cannot cross-justify between sections.

➤ "a bare declaration as a body: flagged, no crash"
{
  Declare P
  «:[s , [m , (P s m)] ]» ⊘
}

➤ "a declaration nested in an environment body: flagged, no crash"
{
  Declare N, Q
  «:[u , { (N u) [v , (Q u v)] }]» ⊘
}

➤ "the rest of the document validates normally around an unsupported declaration"
{
  Declare R, A, t
  Rule: :{ R(x) }
  «:[w , { (A w) [y , (A y)] }]» ⊘
  R(t) ✔︎
}

➤ "a ForSome with a Let-environment body: flagged, and the interior Let does not crash the preemie sweep"
{
  Declare B
  «[c , { :[z] (B c z) }]» ⊘
}
